{{Redirect|E. J. Dent|the clockmaker|Edward John Dent}}
[[File:Edward J. Dent, 1900.jpg|thumb|Dent at [[King's College, Cambridge]], 1900]]

'''Edward Joseph Dent''', generally known by his initials as '''E. J. Dent''' (16 July 1876, [[Ribston Hall|Ribston]], [[Yorkshire]] – 22 August 1957, [[London]]), was a British writer on music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kings.cam.ac.uk/archive-centre/archive-month/march-2013.html|title=Fields of study: Edward Dent, musicologist|website=www.kings.cam.ac.uk}}</ref>

==Life==
Dent was the son of the landowner and politician [[John Dent (Liberal MP)|John Dent]].  He was educated at [[Eton College|Eton]] and [[King's College, Cambridge]],<ref>{{acad|id=DNT895EJ|name=Dent, Edward Joseph}}</ref> where he sat the Classical Tripos  in 1898. He was elected a [[Fellow]] of the college in March 1902 having distinguished himself in music both as researcher and a composer.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=University intelligence |day_of_week=Monday |date=17 March 1902 |page_number=11 |issue=36717| }}</ref>

Dent was Professor of Music at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]] from 1926 to 1941. He was President of the [[International Society for Contemporary Music|I.S.C.M.]] from its foundation in 1922 until 1938 and was President of the International Music Society between 1931 and 1949. He was a governor of [[Sadler's Wells Opera]], and translated many [[libretto|libretti]] for it. He wrote influential books on [[Alessandro Scarlatti]], [[Ferruccio Busoni]], [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]], [[Opera in English|English operas]] and the operas of [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]].

He was a Fellow of the [[British Academy]] and was awarded honorary degrees from [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], Cambridge and [[Harvard University|Harvard]] Universities. After [[World War I]], Dent sought to bring together the artistic communities of the two countries. After his death the [[Royal Musical Association]] instituted the Dent Medal for work in musicology.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Papers of Edward Joseph Dent|website=Archives Hub (archiveshub.jisc.ac.uk)|url=https://archiveshub.jisc.ac.uk/search/archives/bf7f54d0-10e9-38b0-b263-9454edd5c0a8}}</ref>

